# Frontend ↔ Backend Integration Contract

Your frontend (`client/`) has its own rules for structure, styling, and
rendering strategy. This file only defines the points where frontend code
must line up with the backend (`server/`) so the two never drift apart.

## 1. Types and validation — per app, aligned by contract

- **Client** request/response shapes and Zod form schemas live in
  `client/lib/types/` and are imported across the frontend — never redeclare
  API entity shapes inline in components.
- **Server** request DTOs and domain types live in each module's `*.dto.ts`
  and `*.types.ts`, with cross-module helpers in `server/shared/`.
- Client and server each maintain their own types/schemas. When adding or
  changing an API field, update **both** sides to match the contract below.
- If the frontend needs a Zod schema for form validation that mirrors an API
  DTO, define it in `client/lib/types/` following the same field rules as
  the server's `*.dto.ts` — do not import across the client/server boundary.

## 2. API client — one place, not scattered fetches

- All HTTP calls to `server/` go through a single typed client module
  (wherever your frontend rules place it) — never inline
  `fetch('/api/v1/...')` calls inside components.
- The client always talks to `/api/v1/...` — respect backend versioning;
  never hit an unversioned or `/api/v2` path unless the backend has
  actually moved to it.
- Base URL comes from an env var (e.g. `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` or equivalent),
  never hardcoded.

## 3. Response envelope — unwrap consistently

Every backend response follows:
```json
// success
{ "success": true, "data": { }, "meta": { } }
// error
{ "success": false, "error": { "code": "...", "message": "...", "details": [] } }
```
- The API client unwraps `data` for callers and throws a typed
  `ApiError(code, message, details)` on `success: false`, so components/hooks
  never manually check `response.success`.
- `meta` (pagination info) is passed through to list-consuming
  hooks/components as-is — don't reshape it ad hoc per feature.

## 4. Error handling on the client

- Map backend error `code`s (e.g. `PRODUCT_NOT_FOUND`, `VALIDATION_ERROR`,
  `UNAUTHORIZED`) to user-facing messages in one place (an error-message
  map), not with scattered string comparisons across components.
- `UNAUTHORIZED`/expired-token errors trigger the shared auth-refresh flow
  (see below) before surfacing an error to the user.

## 5. Auth flow

- Access token: kept in memory (or short-lived storage per your frontend
  rules) and sent as `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on every API client
  request.
- Refresh token: httpOnly secure cookie, never accessible to JS — the
  browser sends it automatically to the refresh endpoint.
- The API client has a single 401-handling interceptor: on a 401, attempt
  one silent refresh via the backend's refresh endpoint, retry the original
  request once, then force logout if the refresh also fails. This logic
  lives in one place, not duplicated per feature/service call.

## 6. Idempotency for sensitive actions

- Checkout/order-creation/payment calls from the frontend must attach an
  `Idempotency-Key` header (generate a UUID client-side per checkout
  attempt) to match the backend's idempotency handling — prevents duplicate
  orders on double-click or network retry.

## 7. Pagination contract

- List views send `page`/`limit` query params matching the backend's
  defaults (`page=1`, `limit=20`, max `100`) and read `meta.total` for
  pagination UI — don't invent a different pagination scheme client-side.

## 8. Environment/config alignment

- Any value the frontend needs that originates from backend config (e.g.
  supported currencies, max upload size, feature flags) should be exposed
  via a dedicated `GET /api/v1/config` endpoint rather than duplicated as a
  hardcoded constant in the frontend.

## 9. What NOT to do

- Don't call MongoDB, Redis, or any infrastructure service directly from
  `client/` — everything goes through `server/`.
- Don't reimplement backend business logic (pricing, discounts, stock
  checks) on the frontend for anything other than optimistic UI — the
  backend is always the source of truth and re-validates on submit.
